e the state board of education. 4.'),(5284,79,2,45,0,'WPR'),(5285,79,2,40,0,'1987-04'),(5286,79,2,47,0,'CC'),(5287,79,2,46,0,'Wages'),(5288,79,2,43,0,'3480075'),(5289,79,2,38,0,'Florida'),(5290,79,2,1,0,'FEA/UNITED PRESIDENT \'PAT TORNILLO\'S COMMENTS BEFORE THE STATE BOARD OF EDUCATION APRIL 2J 1987\r\n\r\nTHIS ISSUE BEFORE YOU TODAY IS PROBABLY THE MOST IMPORTANT EDUCATION ISSUE TO Cor1E BEFORE THIS CABINET. THE CAREER LADDER RULES YOU ARE BEING ASKED TO ADOPT ARE THE FOUNDATION BLOCKS UPON WHICH THIS STATE CAN DRAMATICALLY IMPROVE ITS EDUCATION DELIVERY SYSTEM. 23 OUT OF 29 OF OUR LOCALS HAVE NEGOTIATED ACAREER LADDER . PLAN WITH THEIR SCHOOL BOARDS. THE MAJORITY OF THOSE PLANS HAVE BEEN RATIFIED.\' THOUSANDS OF OUR TEACHERS. HAVE TAKEN UP THE CHALLENGE LAID OUT BY THE RAYMOND B. STEWART CAREER ACHIEVEMENT .. LEGISLATION. THEY HAVE PROVEN THEIR READINESS WILLINGNESS AND . ABILITY TO WORK IN AFULL \'PARTNERSHIP WITH THEIR LOCAL SCHOOL BOARDS TO BRI NG ABOUT EFFECT.IVE CHANGE.\'\r\n.\r\n~.\r\n\r\n.\r\n\r\n.\r\n\r\nJ\r\n\r\n.\r\n\r\nOUR MEMBERS OVERC,~ME THEIR DISTRUST OF THE SYSTEM\'S ABILITY TO DELIVER AND TOOK THE FIRST STEP TOWARD THE PROFESSIONALIZATION OF TEACHI NG THERE WERE MANY HURDLES LONG HOURS OF NEGOTIATIONS J PLANNING AND COMPROMISE THAT WENT INTO THOSE 23 PLANS.\r\nI\'\r\n\r\nJ\'\r\n\r\nATTRACTING AND RETAINING THE BEST TEACHERS FOR OUR CHILDREN IS ONE STEP CLOSER TO REALITY INTHESE COUNT IES .\' BUT I MUST SAY . HEREJ THAT THIS CAREER LADDER PLAN IS\' NOT THE TOTAL ANSWER TO ALL\r\n\r\n-2-\r\n\r\nTHE PROBLEMS IN THE STATE\'S EDUCATION SYSTEM, TEACHER MORALE IS AT AN ALL TIME LOW,\' THEY ARE DISILLUSIONED AND FRUSTRATED,\' THEY HAVE HEARD THE CRI ES FOR EDUCATION REFORM BEFORE,\' THEY HAVE BEEN BURNED TOO MANY TIMES BY ILL-CONCEIVED PLANS. THEY WANT REFORM THAT IS GOING TO MAKE ACHANGE IN THEIR CLASSROOM TODAY, TEACHERS ARE BURIED UNDER AGROWING STACK OF PAPERWORK FRUSTRATED BY RECORD-KEEPING TO JUSTIFY THEIR DAILY EFFORTS DISTRAUGHTED BY LACK OF RESPECT FOR THOSE EFFORTS AND OVERWHELMED BY THE GROWING LACK OF PARENTAL CONCERN,\r\nJ J\r\n\r\nTHE BUSINESS .LEADERS OF THIS COUNTRY ARE SAYING THAT IMPROVING THIS NATION\'S EDUCATION SYSTEM IS CRITICAL TO OUR SURVIVAL AS AN . . ECONOMIC POWER AND THAT TEACHERS ARE THE KEY PART OF THAT PROCESS, THEY NOW REALIZE \\~HAT WE IN EDUCATION HAVE BEEN SAYING FOR YEARS THAT THE FACTORY MODEL SCHOOL SYSTEM WE PRESENTLY HAVE IS NOT GOING TO SOLVE THIS .NATION\'S AND THIS \'STATE\'S PROBLEMS, .\r\nJ\r\n\r\nTHIS CALL\' FOR ACHANGE IN ATTITUDE ABOUT TEACHERS AND OUR SCHOOL SYSTEM IS ECHOED BY THE BUSINESS LEADERS IN THE STATE THE ZWICK COMMISSION . THE FLORIDA CHAMBER OF COMMERCE AND THE COUNCIL OF 100) AS WELL AS NUMEROUS EDITORIAL BOARDS \"\r\nJ J\r\n\r\nTHE PUBLIC WANTS ITS TEACHERS TEACHING) NOT ENGULFED IN SOME BUREAUCRATIC MAZE OF REGULATION AND SWAMPED BY PAPERWORK. THE PUBLIC IS BEGINNING TO REALIZE THAT QUALITY TEACHER INVOLVEMENT IS THE ANSWER TO THIS COUNTRY\'S MAJOR PROBLEMS OF ILLITERACY DROPOUTS AND LACK OF CRITI.CAL THINKING SKILLS,\r\nJ\r\n\r\nAS I HAVE SAID BEFORE~ THIS CAREER ACHIEVEMENT PROGRAM IS NOT PERFECT. \' NOR IS IT THE TOTAL ANSWER}\' BUT IT IS ABEG INN ING AND WE HAVE KEPT OUR PART OF THE BARGAIN,\' IT IS No\\~ UP THE BUSINESS COMMUNITY AND THE LEGISLATURE TO KEEP THEIR PART OF THE BARGAIN. THE BUSINESS COMMUNITY NEEDS TO SUPPORT THE TAXES NECESSARY TO FUND THE PROPOSED TEACHER SALARY INCREASE AND THE $90 MILLION FOR THE CAREER ACHIEVEMENT PROGRAM\',\'\r\n,\r\n,\r\n\r\nTHE LEGISLATURE, SHOULD PUT THOSE TAX REVENUES INTO SALARY .. INCREASES AND FULLY FUND THE CAREER ACHIEVEMENT PROGRAM,\r\n\'.\r\n\'\r\n\r\nIF THESE PLAYERS DO NOT KEEP THEI RWORD} THI S CAREER LADDER, PLAN AND ANY FUTURE INCENTIVE PLAN \'WILL BE ADEAD ISSUE, I CALL ON EACH OF YOU TO PROVIDE THE LEADERSHIP NECESSARY} TO USE ALL THE POLITICAL CLOUT OF YOUR OFFICE THIS SESSION AND BEYOND TO HELP TRANSFORM THIS PLAN INTO\' ADYNAMIC BEGINNING. I BELIEVE THAT THE QUALITY OF \'TEACHERS WE WI LL HAVE IN OUR CLASSROOMS . TWO YEARS AND TEN YEARS FROM NOW\', WI LL INLARGE PART DEPEND ON THE BEGINNING WE MAKE THIS SESSION.\r\n\r\n'),(6725,80,2,49,0,'Education Reform'),(6726,80,2,41,0,'The Career development plan for Charlotte- Mecklenberg Schools'),(6727,80,2,39,0,'Charlotte-Mecklenberg (NC) Federation of Teachers'),(6728,80,2,48,0,'Charlotte-Mecklenburg Federation of Teachers,. (1984-85). Charlotte-Mecklenburg Schools Career Development Plan. 34.'),(6729,80,2,45,0,'WPR'),(6730,80,2,40,0,'1984-1985'),(6731,80,2,47,0,'CC'),(6732,80,2,46,0,'Wages'),(6733,80,2,43,0,'3480076'),(6734,80,2,38,0,'Charlotte, NC'),(6735,80,2,1,0,'.\' ..\r\nt\r\n\r\n~-\r\n\r\n.\r\n\"\'fa\r\n\r\n~\r\n\r\n... :\r\n\r\nCHARLOnt-MEtKLEN8URC\r\n\r\nSCHOOt.s CAICÂ£Â£R\r\n\r\nDEVELOPIOT PUN\r\n\r\n\"\r\n\r\npl.n, under dev.lo,..nt fcw the .chool ye.r, IIIOUld provide. \"c.reer I.dder\" th.t , âˆ‘âˆ‘d to 1.I.rl âˆ‘âˆ‘ equlv.l.nt to ~Id-.. n.g... nt p.y r.ngel for t âˆ‘âˆ‘ cherl. The pl.n hli. rob.tl could period for t âˆ‘âˆ‘cher. which strel~es profelllon.1 develo,..nt. During the Inltl.1 prob.tfonory on:~!\' t.,cher, ~.t fa-plete Inlervlc. r.qulr.mentl .quiv.l.nt to . . . ,ter\', degree .nd h.v. I.tl,f.:: \' on-the-job p.r ot.ance evalu.tionl. Ch.nge$ .. de In the tenure \'y,t. . .xtend the prob.tlonary ,:;rod t ,-, yo.r., but provide. flexible tl .. fr.~ for .chi.vlng t.nur. ,t.tUI. \'0\r\ntIM)\r\n\r\n\'\'\'\'-\'5\r\n\r\nfa [I ialbl.?\r\nAll t âˆ‘âˆ‘ cherl new to the Iystem would partlclp.t., with .xperl.nc.d te.chen I\" the IYlt_ hovlng the opportunity to Join If they wi,hld to do\r\n\r\n\'0.\r\n\r\n:\r\n\r\nOttlill of the Plln: Prob.tlon.ry St.tu,: (.ee b.ck of p.ge) \'irst yâˆ‘âˆ‘ r - .11 te.ch.r, .re probltlon.ry Second y~.r - .dv.nce to clreer nominee It.tu\" continue II prob.tlon.ry te.cher, or be t.r.tn.ted Third ye.r - .dy.nce to c.reer cendld.te, .dv.nc. to c.r.. r nominee, r... ln c.r.. r naalne. or be termin.ted , Fourth year - .dv.nce to career c.ndld.testatu\" r\",\'n., c.reer noII